# Error Handling & Logging

## Poller failures

When a weather API fetch fails, log at WARNING level with three mandatory fields — city name, HTTP status code (or exception type if no response), and the retry/attempt count if applicable. Do NOT raise the exception. Continue to the next city. Example:

```python
logger.warning(
    "HTTP error fetching %s: status=%s url=%s",
    city_name,
    exc.response.status_code,
    exc.request.url,
)
return
```

Use `%s` printf-style formatting in all logger calls — never f-strings — so that log filtering tools can match on the format string.

## Deduplication constraint violations

When a `sqlalchemy.exc.IntegrityError` is caught due to a duplicate (city, reading_time) pair, log at DEBUG level with the city and timestamp. Do NOT re-raise. Do NOT call `detect_events` for that reading.

```python
logger.debug(
    "Duplicate reading for %s at %s — skipping",
    reading.city,
    reading.reading_time,
)
db.rollback()
return
```

## Unexpected exceptions in the poll cycle

Catch unexpected exceptions at the top of `poll_all_cities` with a bare `except Exception:`. Log at ERROR with `exc_info=True` so the full traceback is preserved. Do NOT re-raise — the APScheduler job must survive individual cycle failures.

## Database session lifecycle

Every function that opens a `SessionLocal()` must close it in a `finally` block. FastAPI route handlers use the `get_db` dependency which handles this automatically.

## Event detection failures

If `detect_events` raises, log the error and commit the reading without events rather than rolling back the entire insertion. A reading without events is better than losing a reading entirely.
